@zealotpb : You can try bazel 0.24.1 as suggested by @wcq19941215  and let us know if that helps. Thanks!

I will mention the reason bazel 0.25.0 is not supported yet (because I think that is the question being asked) is that bazel 0.25.0 was only released 9 ago and has not been tested with the tensorflow builds. New bazel versions have a long history of breaking the tensorflow builds, so the recommendation is the build with the versions that have been tested.

The release notes for bazel 0.25.0 list 6 incompatible changes from the 0.24.0 version of bazel, so this new version of bazel could very well break the current TensorFlow build. In time it will be tested and supported.

Once Bazel 1.0 is released we won't have that many incompatible changes between versions which are released so frequently (there's a bazel 0.25.1 out already). At that point we will be able to support a wider range of versions, at the moment the corresponding line in `./configure.py` uses exactly one Bazel version, the one that we are confident TensorFlow builds with: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/be23374b52af36e3cad3a6a7a5bd58634c29755c/configure.py#L1391

title: Allow sharing of TensorBundles across big- and little-endian architectures
body:
This PR contains changes that allow machines with big-endian architectures to load TensorFlow checkpoints that were written on a little-endian machine; and vice versa. The approach I use is that which was discussed in [this thread on TensorFlow-Dev](https://groups.google.com/a/tensorflow.org/d/msg/developers/GOzGNx8GnHg/oxBFij5ACAAJ). Specifically, I have modified `BundleReader::GetValue()` such that it byte-swaps tensors as needed while reading in TensorBundles.

This change set should allow us to close issues #11290, #16003, and #16364.

Here's a more specific list of changes:
* I have modified the endianness check in the `BundleReader` constructor. Instead of raising an error when it detects a bundle of incompatible endianness, the constructor now sets a flag `need_to_swap_bytes_`.
* `BundleReader::GetValue` now byte-swaps the elements of numeric tensors if the `need_to_swap_bytes_` flag is set.
* I have added a cross-platform set of byte-swapping routines at `tensorflow/core/util/tensor_bundle/byte_swap.[cc|h]`. This step took a while. Converting between byte orders is remarkably un-standardized across operating systems. For the low-level swapping operations, I use Linux's built-in library routines when available, then fall back on `htonl`/`htons` on non-Linux little-endian machines, then fall back on universal macros for all other systems.
* Because the byte-swapping code will be different on different machines, I have included a fairly robust suite of regression tests. I have run these tests on Linux/x86_64 and on MacOS/x86_64. Some colleagues of mine at IBM are performing additional testing on OS/390, which has a big-endian processor architecture.

Limitations of the current implementation:
* I did not implement byte-swapping for `VariantTensors`. If `BundleReader` encounters a bundle that contains a variant tensor and has an incompatible byte order, the class will return `errors::Unimplemented`.
* The byte-swapping code does not use SIMD instructions to perform byte-swapping operations. It byte-swaps tensors one element at a time.

title: Supporting control flow in TensorFlow Lite
body:
This is a tracking ticket for supporting generalized control flow in TensorFlow Lite. See also the [RFC](https://github.com/tensorflow/community/pull/83). 

At this moment, if you see missing ops like "Switch", "Merge", "Enter", "Exit", "NextIteration" when converting a TensorFlow model to TensorFlow Lite, it means the graph contains control flows, and there's no way to convert it. 

We're working hard to enable this feature. Updates will be posted here.

title: Always-on dropout layer
body:
**Describe the feature and the current behavior/state.**

Add the ability to create always-on dropout layers.

**Will this change the current api? How?**

Yes, adds a boolean option `always_on` to `tf.keras.layers.Dropout`.

Currently, implementing this functionality requires writing a custom dropout layer:

```py
class Dropout(tf.keras.layers.Layer):
    """Always-on dropout layer, i.e. does not respect the training flag
    set to true by model.fit but false by model.predict.
    Unlike tf.keras.layers.Dropout, this layer does not return input
    unchanged if training=true, but always randomly drops a fraction specified
    by self.size of the input nodes.
    """

    def __init__(self, rate, **kwargs):
        super().__init__(**kwargs)
        self.rate = rate

    def call(self, inputs):
        return tf.nn.dropout(inputs, self.rate)

    def get_config(self):
        """enables model.save and restoration through tf.keras.models.load_model"""
        config = super().get_config()
        config["rate"] = self.rate
        return config
```

**Who will benefit from this feature?**

Everyone using dropout to create Bayesian neural networks ([see this paper](https://arxiv.org/abs/1703.04977)). In particular, users of `tfp` may be interested.
